{"cursor":"10898","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In nuclear fusion research, the 'Lawson criterion', first derived on fusion\nreactors (initially classified) by John D. Lawson in 1955 and published in\n1957, J. D. Lawson, \"Some Criteria for a Power Producing Thermonuclear\nReactor\", Proceedings of the Physical Society B, Volume 70 (1957), p. 6 is\nan important general measure of a system that defines the conditions needed for\na fusion reactor to reach 'ignition', that is, that the heating of the plasma by\nthe products of the fusion reactions is sufficient to maintain the temperature\nof the plasma against all losses without external power input. As originally\nformulated the Lawson criterion gives a minimum required value for the product\nof the plasma (electron) density n e and the \"energy confinement time\"\nÏ E. Later analyses suggested that a more useful figure of merit is\nthe \"triple product\" of density, confinement time, and plasma temperature T. The\ntriple product also has a minimum required value, and the name \"Lawson\ncriterion\" often refers to this inequality.\n","linknr":353,"url":"Lawson_criterion","recorded":1362512787,"links":59,"instances":["physics_articles","physics","scientist"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Fusion power"],"headings":["The product ''n''<sub>e</sub>''&tau;''<sub>E</sub>","The \"triple product\" ''n''<sub>e</sub>''T&tau;''<sub>E</sub>","Inertial confinement","See also","Notes","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/2/4c257f6a98adb49d49d3981e623e9316.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/c/4/1c47ae1a3c72a4657980433b7a835897.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/8/d/78d16c56922c78bce22f8d3b97429957.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/6/5/46578e4e1dc07dd17966feba118035e6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/9/9/499ea482f0642e2bd203a3f560d4dd97.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/6/1/161fddc79b30ddbd8d4d76c1a91b1d63.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/9/0/f90b1e75c8e76bc8ebb6e95311644016.png","//